{"name":"Appendix F - Monsters","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Errol Athersen","type":"text","_id":"rgevuWe0ngfwlZhN","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Captain @UUID[Actor.jDhZLmJMf1mzbi6g]{Errol Athersen} is a legend upon the high seas. Master of the Fairy Queen, a lightweight clipper famed for its daring exploits and far-flung adventures at the very edges of the world, the captain is the subject of persistent, often outlandish rumours and tall tales. Some say he is more fey than man, others that he is a spirit lost at sea – what his crew know of him is that he is daring, composed under pressure, and almost supernaturally attuned to the ebb and flow of the sea.</p><p>In truth, Errol is an escapee from the legendary Isles of Thess, where his family have served as holy warriors under the isles’ priesthood for generations. Unlike all before him, Errol was born a twin, and never seemed to have quite the magical power or appropriate temperament of his brother Flynn. Convinced that he was unnecessary and bored beyond imagining by life upon the isles, he braved its treacherous coasts and escaped out into the world, embarking upon a life of adventure and excitement.</p><p><strong>Heir of Storms</strong>. Unbeknownst to Errol, he is a direct descendant of the goddess Thess, and carries in him the power of one of her aspects – the reckless, turbulent Maiden of Storms. This is why he has not aged in almost twenty years, and where his innate magic springs from.</p><p><strong>Singular Focus</strong>. Errol is reckless and easily bored, and can nurse a grudge for decades, but he has the focus and determination of a born leader. He can be single-minded, but rarely seems to lose his composure, channeling his stormy nature into a seemingly endless wellspring of resolve.</p><p><strong>Expert Duelist</strong>. Errol is a legendary duellist, far more comfortable with the flash and flicker of steel than with the magic in his blood, and has merged the two into an eclectic fighting style.<br /></p><section class=\"secret\" id=\"secret-6eEmPz9cWI18iLjy\"><p>GM Notes :</p><blockquote><p>Read out: “Standing at ease with his palm rested atop the hilt of an ornate sabre, the man before you has angular, fierce features and messy dark hair, his bright blue eyes sweeping over you. Certainly no older than mid-twenty, he wears a loose, airy shirt and rugged breeches, and from his shoulders hangs a sailing coat.”</p></blockquote></section>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Flynn Athersen","type":"text","_id":"s3scgj3piJ12dYZC","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>High Protector of the Isles of Thess, @UUID[Actor.ehj97RwB6oE1augC]{Flynn Athersen} serves directly under Lady Sarenya, the high priestess of its temple. For generations, men and women of his magically-gifted line have performed this sacred duty, acting as sacral guardians whose responsibilities range from leading particular religious ceremonies to fighting very real threats to the isles. Flynn performs this duty gladly, his steady, kind nature well-suited to the life of structure and caregiving it requires.</p><p><strong>Heir of Tides.</strong> Unbeknownst to Flynn, he is more than a simple guardian – he carries in him a shard of the goddess Thess’ power, serving as the avatar for her steady, protective aspect as the Tidemother.<br />Sworn Protector. Flynn is calm and composed, and naturally predisposed toward caring for others. He takes his responsibilities seriously and rarely loses his temper, but can be a fierce fighter when those he cares for are threatened.</p><p><strong>Power of Thess</strong>. The power in Flynn’s blood grants him exceptional magical abilities – mastery not only over the wind and tides, but also the power to channel the light of the moon and abjure evil.<br /></p><section class=\"secret\" id=\"secret-jQODtosTRs570jaG\"><p>GM Notes :</p><blockquote><p>Read out: “The glassy-eyed man standing stock still on one side of the room is an almost perfect reflection of his brother, but his cloth is far less ostentatious – he wears a long, flowing robe tied at his waist by a simple rope, a cloak the colour of moonlight falling from his shoulders. A sword hangs idly at his hip, and a long, wooden staff has been discarded at his feet.”</p></blockquote><p></p></section>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Lady Sarenya","type":"text","_id":"LBIL03FeGRrXTSVU","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Long ago,  @UUID[Actor.c3A66qaEzxRxcXs8]{Lady Sarenya} was merely a lantern girl in the service of Thess’ temple. Her life was upended when she developed a strange wasting condition, all efforts to stall the disease failing. When Thess did not answer her prayers, her desperation attracted the eye of the Elder One, and it called out to her. Determined to survive, Sarenya descended into the deepest reaches of the isles. There, the Elder One waited, its pungent, translucent blood oozing from its cage.</p><p>At its direction, she drank the foul liquid, and was transformed by it. She became an aquatic abomination, neither living nor dead, blessed with powerful psychic abilities but cursed with a hunger for the blood of the living. Sarenya had become the first and mightiest of the Thessidian vampires.</p><p>It did not take long for Sarenya to establish a stranglehold upon the isles. With her powers of hypnosis she subverted Thess’ priesthood from within, and with her unholy strength she tore apart all who stood in her way. Now, she looks toward the future, and seeks a way to rejuvenate her dread master to its full strength.</p><p><strong>Shadow Queen. </strong>Sarenya is a cunning and experienced manipulator. She is well practiced at maneuvering mortals like puppets against one another, and her ability to read thoughts makes her an expert at drawing out the weaknesses of her foes.</p><p><strong>Survivor.</strong> The centuries have eaten away at Lady Sarenya’s humanity and her empathy, but the will to survive that drove her into the Elder One’s service remains. Sarenya is desperate to perpetuate her existence, and to do so, she must ensure that her master is satisfied. She clings tenaciously to unlife and will do whatever it takes to ensure her own survival.<br /></p><section class=\"secret\" id=\"secret-SrTojUFkFAeHle9N\"><p>GM Notes :</p><blockquote><p>Read out: “Water flows from the towering creature as it pulls itself up out of the depths, running along its immense crest of fins and glistening scales. Its upper body is that of a pale, slender woman, graceful fins running like banners from its arms. Beneath the waist, its form splits grotesquely into a squirming mass of long, eel-like tendrils, each one thicker than your own midsection. A great spear gleams in its grasp, pointing in your direction, and it distends its jaw unnaturally to release a keening, inhuman screech…”</p></blockquote></section>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":400000,"name":"Plo'orgk","type":"text","_id":"ogn7rP5kC4v8xfE5","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>A frogman from the steaming farlands, @UUID[Actor.2VAkIoFc7ilbs8ga]{Plo’orgk} is a seasoned hunter, having spent much of his life prowling the mangrove warrens of his home in search of unwary prey. Cursed with a distinctive yellow-blue flesh tone considered unlucky by his people, he has always been something of an outsider, and eventually found companionship with Captain Errol’s crew aboard the Fairy Queen.</p><p>As the crew’s tracker, Plo’orgk has had the opportunity to test his skills against the most dangerous and elusive prey the world has to offer.</p><p><strong>Competitor</strong>. Plo’orgk often seems stoic and difficult to read, and has little need for small talk or consistent interaction with others. Despite this, though, he is a proud creature, and has a strong competitive streak.<br /></p><section class=\"secret\" id=\"secret-Agoim7sphuTm77RO\"><p>GM Notes :</p><blockquote><p>Read out: “The creature before you is a strange mingling of man and frog, its glistening skin a mixture of blues and yellows, and its large, watery eyes regardingly you blankly. Ornaments of bone hang like trophies from about its neck, and adorn the length of its arms, and it holds in one webbed hand a large, serrated spear of rough ivory…”</p></blockquote></section>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":500000,"name":"Stormbringer Leviathan","type":"text","_id":"Q9E31wa6akhnrWLP","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>In ages past, the @UUID[Actor.TlXJHd1o3F3FFtnj]{Stormbringer Leviathan} were legion. They were creations of the goddess Thess, tasked with carrying out her will and delivering her terrible vengeance. As the time of gods waned, though, so did their numbers, until only one remained.</p><p>The last stormbringer has guarded the waters of the Isles of Thess for longer than any man or woman can remember. Its lonely vigil, however, was interrupted by Lady Sarenya after her ascent to power. The ancient vampire used her psychic might and corrupting blood to bend Thess’ last guardian to her will. Now, the leviathan serves as her personal monster, tearing apart the few ships that make it to the isles intact.</p><p><strong>Eye of the Storm</strong>. Stormbringer leviathans are storms made flesh, their bodies crafted by Thess around a seething core of elemental power. Wherever these creatures go, the sky darkens and the wind howls, bringing ruin to all in their wake.<br /></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":600000,"name":"The Elder One","type":"text","_id":"pbNhLrUVB6Upu4cL","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>The @UUID[Actor.v319xp83NWUCSLaz]{The Elder One} is like no being in all the mortal lands, for it is of none of them. A visitor from beyond, the Elder One is a stellar traveller that, in ages past, voyaged from star to star upon a vessel of gleaming black diamond. The Elder One crash-landed upon the Isles of Thess long ago, and was imprisoned beneath them by the last act of Thess herself. Alien and inscrutable, the Elder One seeks constantly to regain its former strength and resume its long sojourn across the cosmos – and it will not hesitate to destroy all those in  its way.</p><p><strong>Eldritch Mind</strong>. The Elder One is an ancient, pitiless evil, its mind unlike that of any mortal. Its thoughts alone disturb the very air around it, and its psyche falls like a hammer upon the minds of those faced by it, enslaving them to its will or destroying them utterly.</p><p><strong>Alien Nature.</strong> A creature apart from those of the natural world, the Elder One’s very being radiates corruption. Its touch distorts flesh and warps minds, reshaping creatures to be more akin to itself.</p><section class=\"secret\" id=\"secret-QGjuRYL7uG9M8Kfr\"><p>GM Notes :</p><blockquote><p>Read out: “Three great, blazing red eyes pulse with power along the front of the strange creature, an immense maw like that of a lamprey opening just under them. Its pale, slippery flesh is formed into a shape halfway between that of an eel, a fish, and malformed lump of clay, fins swaying along its back and thick tendrils coiling from its body. A long, powerful tail hangs behind it, flexing and flicking as it moves, and the air around the creature seems to quiver with invisible power…”</p></blockquote><p></p></section>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":700000,"name":"Thessidian Ancient","type":"text","_id":"7ocFru77Y2Z9oKbE","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Ancients are those Thessidian vampires that have endured the test of time and survived to see their powers swell and their bodies mutate beyond the limitations of the younger kin. Each and every ancient is several centuries old, and has preyed upon generation after generation of innocents to feed its unnatural hunger.</p><p><strong>Psychic Power.</strong> , @UUID[Actor.yCHpd535YTJxT9ja]{Thessidian Ancient} like all Thessidian vampires, are the spawn of Lady Sarenya and the dreaded Elder One, and they have inherited the latter’s psionic might. As they grow older, their power grows until they can enthrall all but the strongest of minds – and shred those that will not be bent.</p><p><strong>Oceanic Mutation</strong>. After the first few hundred years of a Thessidian’s unlife, their body undergoes a terrible transformation. Their flesh warps, legs melding into a sinuous, eel-like appendage, and they grow to prodigious sizes.<br /></p><section class=\"secret\" id=\"secret-Pfy2eiv4ltvPK95g\"><p>GM Notes :</p><blockquote><p>Read out: “Before you is a young woman with deathly pale skin and long, dark hair that streaks wetly across her body. She wears only rags, and gills line the flesh beneath her ribs. Slender, sharp fins protrude from her forearms and the sides of her head.”</p></blockquote></section>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":800000,"name":"Thessidian Drowner","type":"text","_id":"QirWwdeKZEQwcDkH","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Vampires of the Thessidian breed are an unstable mutation born from the blood of an elder aberration. As one might expect, the process does not always take. Such failures arise as horrific parodies of the human form, distended and twisted beyond the size and shape of a human being and covered in glistening weaves of manta-like flesh. These creatures are barely more intelligent than animals, but their strength and speed outstrips that of most of Sarenya’s spawn, and they are blindly obedient to their creator.</p><p><strong>Barbed Tail</strong>. A @UUID[Actor.yfoZW05TzPyqsLeG]{Thessidian Drowner} serrated, whiplike tail carries within its tip a potent toxin that seeps into the veins of its prey and gradually paralyzes it.</p><p><strong>Deep-Sea Predators.</strong> Drowners are adept underwater hunters. They typically wait in large bodies of water for unsuspecting prey, and will drag their catches deep under the waves before feasting upon them.<br /></p><section class=\"secret\" id=\"secret-ABfQlVQ5md2BMxHC\"><p>GM Notes :</p><blockquote><p>Read out: “The loping, spindly creature before you stands several heads higher than any man, and rears up on a pair of long, almost skeletal legs. Its pallid flesh is smooth and rubbery, unfurling out into manta-like flaps of flesh that hang at its sides, and its mouth is full of needle-thin teeth. A long, barbed tail flicks behind it, a thin black fluid seeping from its tip…”</p></blockquote></section>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":900000,"name":"Thessidian Vampire","type":"text","_id":"iH9J4uUznmCJVzby","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>The vampires of the misted Isles of Thess are not like those of the mainland – they inherit not a curse, but a fell mutation, one originating from an eldritch visitor from the stars. Almost every @UUID[Actor.OexM7P49kBReBBQt]{Thessidian Vampire} began life as a Thessidine, a junior priestess in the temple of Thess, and has impressed their progenitor Sarenya with their loyalty, cunning, or talent. After years of brainwashing and religious indoctrination, these women gladly drink the corrupted blood from Sarenya’s veins before being ritually drowned in saltwater.</p><p>Those with the strength of will to cling to existence rise from the waters as an undead abomination under their mistress’ control.</p><p><strong>Song of Longing</strong>. Thessidian vampires inherit powerful psychic abilities from their progenitor. Most notable among them is the power to imbue their voice with a hypnotic quality that lulls unwary listeners into a trance and draws them to their doom.</p><p><strong>Aquatic Vampires.</strong> The nightwalkers of the misted isles display faint echoes of the Elder One’s aquatic nature – fins, gills, and an uncanny ability to move like quicksilver beneath the water.</p><section class=\"secret\" id=\"secret-4o3QRr9aGGu9m0TQ\"><p>GM Notes :</p><blockquote><p>Read out: “Before you is a young woman with deathly pale skin and long, dark hair that streaks wetly across her body. She wears only rags, and gills line the flesh beneath her ribs. Slender, sharp fins protrude from her forearms and the sides of her head.”</p></blockquote></section>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.288","createdTime":1665950239705,"modifiedTime":1665976468801,"lastModifiedBy":"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L"},"_id":"2f3mNI4pjB1Da331","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L":3}}
{"name":"Part II - Into the Mist","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"The Isle of Thess","type":"text","_id":"5BEz2nLAYapstM5L","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<img src=\"modules/bloodlords-of-the-deep/journal/000_-_Bloodlords_of_the_Deep/002_-_Part_II_-_Into_The_Mist/000_-_The_Isles_of_Thess/avatar.png\" /><p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">In this section, the characters explore the mist-shrouded Isles of Thess in search of Errol and his brother, and come into conflict with the dark forces under Lady Sarenya’s command.</span></p><h3 data-anchor=\"the-isles-of-thess\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:1rem 0px 0.5rem;padding:0px;font-weight:normal;font-size:1.25em;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-underline-header);color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong>The Isles of Thess</strong></span></h3><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">There are technically three Isles of Thess, forming a small chain that stretches only slightly over a hundred miles from northwest to southeast, but the characters have landed on Ulune, the central island.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Much of the island is characterized by steep, rolling hills covered by lush green grass. Though there are smatterings of forest, they are significantly inland, and throughout most of the island the vegetation is limited to sparse shrubbery. Ever-present across the isles is a thick, pale grey fog cover, laid so heavily that the sun is never visible.</span></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Navigating the Island","type":"text","_id":"7Hlpzx5SvQ1CPg7c","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>No matter where they have landed, the characters will have to find their way across the island if they wish to ever find Errol or his brother – but the Isles of Thess are not easy to traverse.</p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>The Mist</strong></span>. The cloud of mist that shrouds the isles is a constant one – no matter the season, no matter the weather, the mist remains. Unless characters are indoors, everything more than 20 ft. away from them is treated as lightly obscured, and everything more than 60 ft. away is heavily obscured. This presents an incredible challenge when navigating the isles, and whenever characters are travelling without using a clear path (as indicated on the map above), they must make a DC 16 Wisdom (Survival) check every time they wish to travel for more than an hour. Should they fail, they wander aimlessly for an extra 2 hours before finding their destination.</p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>Dogged Pursuit</strong></span>. If the characters have retrieved @UUID[JournalEntry.qJg4GYQDMSUG8Wxt.JournalEntryPage.73IrpNq3ul3X3c3b]{Aoife Athersen}, getting lost brings greater danger. Should they fail the above Wisdom (Survival) check under these conditions, they risk running into pursuing townsfolk in the fog. They must make a group Dexterity (Stealth) check against a DC of 35 or be attacked by a search party of frenzied townsfolk. They are treated as six Cultists (Basic Rules) and two Berserkers (Basic Rules).</p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>Old Stones</strong></span>. Ancient moss-coated stones stand throughout the Isles of Thess, placed there centuries ago for purposes unknown to its modern inhabitants. Today, these stones act as location markers, and are often used to hang lanterns from, creating tiny islands of light within the fog that help the isles’ inhabitants traverse their dreary homeland without getting lost. Most of the remaining paths on the isles weave their way along formations of these stones.</p><p>The first time the characters progress further inland from any of the Fairy Queen’s potential landing points, read out the following text:</p><blockquote><p>Read out: “Up ahead, a slumped shape waits in the mist. As you approach, it becomes clear that it is a large, moss-draped stone, its surface adorned with faded, spiraling carvings – the largest among them depicting the face of a grim, three-eyed man and beard made of twisting, octopi-like tentacles. Atop the stone, a plank of wood is attached to it by old, damp rope, and upon its end hangs a broken lantern…”</p></blockquote><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>The Deep Mist.</strong></span> In certain areas of the isles, the mist is particularly dense, and brings with it new dangers. In these regions, everything more than 30 ft. away is considered heavily obscured. In addition, there is a constant sense of unease that makes it impossible to get comfortable – long rests cannot be attempted in these areas.</p><p>Finally, the mist here plays strange tricks on the minds of travellers, often leading them astray. Characters that travel through the deep mists for more than an hour find their sense of space and time slipping, their companions often seeming further away or closer than they really are, and see entrancing lights that hover in the distance.</p><p>When characters travel this way, those with the three lowest passive perception scores must succeed on a DC 15 Wisdom (Perception) save or be led away from the rest of the group. Characters searching for them must succeed on a DC 16 Wisdom (Survival) check. Lost characters must make three successive Wisdom (Perception) checks against a DC of 16, 17, and 18. Should they fail all three, the lights lead them over the edge of a steep, rocky cliff roughly 150 ft. high. They must make a DC 17 Dexterity (Acrobatics) check to catch themselves before they fall.</p><p>A character that succeeds on all three checks miraculously makes it back to the rest of the characters. Surely, Thess smiles upon them.</p><p></p><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\"><tbody><tr><td><p></p><h3>Trouble on Thess</h3><p>Not all is well for Lady Sarenya. Despite her incredible supernatural power and her shadowy grip upon the isles’ priesthood, certain matters on the isles have rankled her.</p><p></p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>Aedus</strong></span>. Not everyone on the Isles of Thess has succumbed entirely to Sarenya’s control. A few priests managed to flee when she first established her reign, and squirreled away their own records of the isles’ secret history. Eventually, their chronicles passed into the hands of Aedus, the uncle of  @UUID[JournalEntry.qJg4GYQDMSUG8Wxt.JournalEntryPage.73IrpNq3ul3X3c3b]{Aoife Athersen} on her mother’s side, who spent years plotting escape. <span style=\"background-color:transparent\">Before his attempted </span><span style=\"letter-spacing:0px;background-color:transparent;color:\">departure from the isles, Aedus gifted Aoife with a @UUID[Item.SfRdaO3j8RpjquXu]{Wardstone} and left behind hints that would lead her to find the same truths he did.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>The Wind’s Widow</strong></span>. Just over ten years ago, a trading vessel called the Wind’s Widow somehow crashed off the coast of Ulune – a sign that the power of the mists is weakening. Several doubters of the current reign – including Aedus – seized the opportunity to attempt an escape. Aedus planned to leave the isles, track down Errol, and hand over to him the @UUID[Item.4Fux45QTDbxytGzI]{The Moon Key}. Sarenya succeeded in destroying the ship before it could leave, but the debacle still weighs on her mind.</p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>Dwindling Population</strong></span>. Sarenya has noticed that the population of the isles is entering a freefall. Something about her nefarious manipulations of the mists seems to be slowly strangling the life out of Thess’ people – which means she must effect her master’s rejuvenation sooner rather than later.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Saltvine","type":"text","_id":"1PyBm5XZuTlP0nhm","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Saltvine is the closest village on Ulune to the sea, its loam-topped, cladded buildings clinging to the sides of a steep, grassy hill that descends toward the coast. It is where Errol planned to land the Fairy Queen originally, and was once a quiet but well-populated fishing village.</span></p><blockquote style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px 0.5em 10px;padding:0px 0px 0px 20px;border-left:3px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);font-style:italic;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><em>Read out: (at a distance) “Old, stone-cladded houses huddle together against the side of a grassy hill overlooking the sea. The mist hangs heavily over them, making it hard to tell one from another, and their roofs are turfed with a layer of thick loam. Not one living thing disturbs the silence…”</em></span></p></blockquote><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">As the population of the isles diminished, however, the last few residents of Saltvine moved further inland, into @UUID[.2btWfgI5h1GRHjJW]{Cress} Today, Saltvine is a ghost town, its crumbling houses standing empty and its dirt tracks overgrown by sprawling green grass.</span></p><blockquote style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px 0.5em 10px;padding:0px 0px 0px 20px;border-left:3px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);font-style:italic;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><em>Read out: (in the village) “As you pick your way through the tiny seaside village, it quickly becomes clear that the entire settlement is abandoned – and has been for some time. The turfed rooftops are overgrown and wild, the paths are matted with grass, and the buildings’ silent interiors are empty.”</em></span></p></blockquote><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Old Eamon.</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"> On the inland outskirts of Saltvine, a confused and hurt @UUID[JournalEntry.qJg4GYQDMSUG8Wxt.JournalEntryPage.Q9ard55sHTGmOBei]{Eamon} is sitting on one of the old stone walls that runs along the road out of town, nursing a bloody head wound. Under the influence of the Waning (<em style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">see block text below</em>), Eamon has been wandering the abandoned village, eventually tripping and hurting himself. He doesn’t quite understand where he is or why Saltvine is empty, and can’t remember much beyond his own name.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">If the characters tend to Eamon’s wounds and help him back to @UUID[.2btWfgI5h1GRHjJW]{Cress}, the villagers there are much more welcoming and open to them than they would be otherwise.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"></p><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;width:622px;border-collapse:collapse;background:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);margin:0.5em 0px;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><tbody style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><tr style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><td style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;padding:0.25em 0px 0.25em 2px\"><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"></p><h3 data-anchor=\"the-mists-of-thess\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:1rem 0px 0.5rem;padding:0px;font-weight:normal;font-size:1.25em;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-underline-header)\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The Mists of Thess</span></h3><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Cloak of the Goddess.</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"> The people of the isles believe that the goddess Thess raised the mists that shroud their homeland – and they are correct. The Mists of Thess were conjured by the deity herself, to forever protect the isles in her absence.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Dark Power</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. When Lady Sarenya took power, she used the @UUID[Item.p2QWLnS66byB4SJ1]{Stormspear of Thess} to exert her own control over the mists, subverting the phenomenon for her purposes. The mists now serve as a conduit for her mental powers – and through her, the powers of the Elder One – and let her more easily bend the minds of the isles’ inhabitants.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">The Waning</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. There have been dire consequences for Sarenya’s meddling. Continual exposure to her thought-numbing power through the mists has led to many islanders developing a wasting condition of the mind they call the Waning. Sufferers grow increasingly detached from their own memories and easily confused, and eventually begin to lose their sight. The growing prominence of this condition on the isles is the main reason for its rapid population decline.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Lantern Girls</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. The mists have shaped the culture of the isles, and a notable element of this culture are the Thessidines – junior priestesses of Thess, usually between fifteen and twenty, whose task it is to maintain the network of lanterns that keep the isles’ roads relatively safe to travel. As Ulune is the central island and host to both the Lighthouse and Temple of Thess, Thessidines are a common sight in its populated regions, moving in small groups and clothed in stark, humble grey cloaks and headdresses that cover much of their hair.</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":400000,"name":"Cress","type":"text","_id":"2btWfgI5h1GRHjJW","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Cress is the last populated village on Ulune, and the furthest inland, located roughly nine miles from Saltvine and the closest shoreline. It is made up of an assortment of haphazardly grouped, cladded stone houses with loamed rooftops. Buildings in Cress are often a fair distance from one another, so junior priestesses from the @UUID[.rvX6P3z4HEyiBSCE]{The Tempe of Thess}– called Thessidines by the locals – light lanterns at the corners of many homes.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Rural Folk</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. Cress is home to just under a hundred human villagers, most of them either fishermen or shepherds by trade. A stout, beady-eyed blacksmith by the name of Tarl lives on the edge of town, but there are few quality materials to work with on the isles and the village has little to offer adventurers as experienced as the characters. The few things they can offer, however, are unique oddities not seen beyond the isles in many centuries:</span></p><ol style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;padding:0px 0px 0px 1.5em;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><li style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"> </span><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Moonweed Lighter</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. A type of rare seaweed with potent phosphorescent properties, moonweed – once treated with a precious sap – is used to light the Thessidines’ lanterns, giving them their distinctive, pale glow. Used in a lantern, an ounce of moonweed lighter will produce light for 5 hours, and many homes in Cress keep small stockpiles of the stuff.</span></li><li style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Cleargrass</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. The furry, verdant green moss that grows upon or around the standing stones that litter the isles can have strange curative properties, and is used by islanders to keep the worst of the Waning at bay. When at least 5 ounces of it are properly boiled (a trick nearly every villager in Cress knows), they produce 1 dose of a potent tea that improves eyesight, granting those that consume it advantage on Wisdom (Perception) checks that involve sight for 8 hours.</span></li><li style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Seablouse</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. The local name for an obscure species of jellyfish, an ounce of properly chopped and ground seablouse can grant those that consume it the miraculous ability to double the time they can hold their breath for. Fishermen prize this particular catch, however, and will often charge extortionate prices for even a single ounce – 5 gp or more.</span></li></ol><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Isolated Village</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. The pale, dark-haired people of Cress rarely see outsiders – in fact, none of them can remember the last time people from beyond the isles set foot in their village. Nobody in town has ever laid eyes upon an elf, dwarf, or halfling, let alone rarer creatures such as tieflings or half-orcs. Characters can expect slack-jawed stares from local youths, and a cold, overly-cautious welcome from the village as a whole.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">If the characters wish to make meaningful conversation with any of Cress’ residents, they must first succeed on a DC 14 Charisma (Persuasion) check. The villagers are far more trusting if the characters have returned Eamon to Cress, negating the need for the prior ability check.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Town in Mourning</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. Cress is not a happy place, but the mood is lower than usual when the characters arrive. Just over a week ago, Errol’s brother Flynn – believed to be of a holy bloodline – disappeared after confronting the Stormbringer Leviathan. The villagers believe that he is dead, and the local priestesses have busied themselves with making Aoife Athersen ready to take on her father’s role.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The villagers will be wide-eyed and amazed if the characters tell them that they arrived with Errol, some simply refusing to believe them while others consider this a sign that there may be an end to the isles’ troubles on the horizon.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">The Standing Stone</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. The most notable landmark in Cress is an 30-ft. tall, awkwardly skewed standing stone that juts from the ground at the old village centre. Moss encrusts its surface, and the old stone is inscribed with a detailed depiction of a resplendent female figure with flowing fin-like wings – the goddess Thess – placing the phases of the moon in their proper order. </span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">@UUID[JournalEntry.qJg4GYQDMSUG8Wxt.JournalEntryPage.aUcTxx4HGIcsM8TI]{Siobhan} is lingering at the Standing Stone, and quickly greets the characters, attempting to ingratiate herself with them and determine their purpose in Cress.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"></p><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;width:622px;border-collapse:collapse;background:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);margin:0.5em 0px;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><tbody style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><tr style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><td style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;padding:0.25em 0px 0.25em 2px\"><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"></p><h3 data-anchor=\"lands-between\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:1rem 0px 0.5rem;padding:0px;font-weight:normal;font-size:1.25em;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-underline-header)\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Lands Between</span></h3><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Mythic Duty</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. In the past, the people of Thess were charged by their goddess with maintaining her holy lighthouse and using it to guide lost sailors to the isles from around the world. It was their duty to help such lost souls repair their ships and set them on the correct course home.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Isle of Ghosts</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. Over time, and with Sarenya’s meddling, much of the islanders’ old ways has been forgotten or misinterpreted. Now, they believe that the Isles of Thess are a waypoint between the lands of the living and the dead, a place of rest for sailors that will never return home. The fact that very few travellers ever arrive on Thess anymore, and usually come as lone, washed-up survivors, reinforces this notion. Villagers in Cress are adamant that only the dead reach the isles, and there is no escaping the mist. Many current people of Cress are descendants of shipwrecked sailors who have been accepted into the community.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Word from the Living</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. There is only one way to give the villagers any reason to doubt their belief that the characters are lost souls – by mentioning that they arrived with Errol. This causes a great commotion in town, causing many to consider the possibility that the errant Athersen could have guided living people through the mists.</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><br style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\" /><br style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\" /></span><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">The Mariner’s Rest</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. Near the centre of town, a hundred or so feet from the Standing Stone, is a freehouse called the Mariner’s Rest. A tall, longhouse style dwelling topped with the characteristic loam rooftops of most structures on the isles, the Mariner’s Rest is by far the largest building in Cress. It generally serves as a communal eatery, as well as an occasional resting stop for fishermen from the other isles.</span></p><blockquote style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px 0.5em 10px;padding:0px 0px 0px 20px;border-left:3px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);font-style:italic;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><em>Read out: “Shadows sway and shudder across the high, arched wooden ceiling of the freehouse. To one side, a fire pit flickers and roils, a heavy iron cauldron bubbling over the flame. A sullen, pale-faced man with dark hair glances up at you over it, his eyes widening with alarm as he notes your appearance. Long wooden tables line the walls, and a gaggle of young girls wearing long headdresses stare unblinking in your direction, clearly whispering to one another about your appearance…”</em></span></p></blockquote><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The Mariner’s Rest is owned by a downcast, double-chinned man in his mid-forties called Cliahm (Commoner, Basis Rules), who charges 1 sp for a serviceable meal of stewed lamb and mead, and 2 sp for the right to stay the night.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">There are also several Thessidines, young priestesses of Thess, sharing a mead over one table. They will speculate ferociously on the characters’ presence. If the characters interact with them, they will shyly excuse themselves unless the characters can succeed on a DC 15 Charisma (Persuasion) check, in which case they will be willing to talk at length about life on the island in exchange for stories of the outside world.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">If the characters choose to stay the night, Lady Sarenya’s minions take the opportunity to ambush them shortly before dawn. Using their heightened control over the villagers to place them in a mindless state, three Thessidian Vampires direct eight villagers (Cultists, Basic Rules) to attack the characters in their sleep. The vampires stay safely outside the freehouse, and make a quick escape if it seems that their minions are soon to be defeated.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Should the characters fight them off, the vampires report back to Sarenya, who resorts to instilling a mass-hysteria in Cress’ inhabitants, causing the entire village (with the exception of Aoife) to become murderously hostile. This occurs half an hour after they retreat.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">The Ritual Hut. </strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">On the opposite side of The Standing Stone from The Mariner’s Rest, a group of four young priestesses (Acolytes, Basic Rules) are loitering by the entrance to a large, stone-walled hut. They are keeping watch over Aoife, who is undergoing a succession rite that will officiate her as her father’s replacement. There is a fair amount of foot traffic outside, with priestesses occasionally exchanging shifts, or coming and going to check on Aoife’s condition or bring her fresh water.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Inside, Aoife is stewing in a heady vaporous hallucinogen generated by boiling a paste-like mixture of plant extracts – and, unbeknownst to her, a powder made from Lady Sarenya’s own blood. Officially, the process is supposed to allow heirs to the Athersen line to see beyond the living world and devote themselves fully to their role as Thess’ chosen champions. In truth, it simply makes their minds more pliable to Lady Sarenya’s manipulations, ensuring that she can always control Thess’ heirs.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Aoife’s Trials</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. Aoife is having great difficulty with her current situation. She is still reeling from the assumed loss of her father, and the @UUID[Item.SfRdaO3j8RpjquXu]{Wardstone} she wears around her arm is fighting off the effects of the mixture. She is experiencing disturbing flashes of memory that have been locked away by Sarenya’s minions, recalling small glimpses of the night@UUID[.GzTYxcdIwnMVVDAm]{The Wind's Widow} washed ashore on Ulune and the chaos that ensued, as well as the @UUID[.7Hlpzx5SvQ1CPg7c#trouble-on-thess]{words her uncle Aedus} left with her. She is becoming increasingly worried that these visions are not mere delusions, and is considering an attempt at escaping the hut so she can collect her thoughts in private.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">If the characters enter and explain their mission, she will ask them to take her away from the village. Once she has spent an hour outside the hut, her memories begin to settle and she will recall Aedus’ command to dig beneath his old home in @UUID[.fD0THF61EITZ9TVB]{Llyanys}.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The priestesses that watch the hut’s entrance will turn away all attempts to enter, and scream for help if the characters attempt to force their way inside.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"></p><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;width:622px;border-collapse:collapse;background:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);margin:0.5em 0px;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><tbody style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><tr style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><td style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;padding:0.25em 0px 0.25em 2px\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;color:rgb(231, 99, 99)\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">! Urgency. As Aoife becomes more cognisant of her emerging memories, she also experiences surreal, nightmarish recollections of Sarenya speaking with her minions in the presence of her and other mind-controlled priestesses. She is certain that if they wish to find Errol, they have only two days to do so.</span></span></td></tr></tbody></table><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Mindless Hordes</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">. The villagers of Cress are deep under Lady Sarenya’s control. Should the characters do anything to endanger the vampire’s plans (for example, trying to leave with Aoife) she will drive the villagers into a violent frenzy, using them to hunt down and kill the interlopers. Once the village has been enthralled in this way, villagers converge upon the characters in waves of 1d6 Cultists (Basic Rules) and 1d4 Berserkers (Basic Rules) every round, and will attempt to pursue them out of town. Their enraged sounds are audible across the village, as they seek out the characters in a blind fury.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Villagers controlled this way can communicate with one another, but are clearly out of their minds, their eyes visibly misted over.</span></p><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;width:622px;border-collapse:collapse;background:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);margin:0.5em 0px;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><tbody style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><tr style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><td style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;padding:0.25em 0px 0.25em 2px\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;color:rgb(231, 99, 99)\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">! Hypnotic Triggers. Siohbhan’s connection to her vampiric mistress allows her to commune with Sarenya at a distance. As such, she can inform the vampire when the characters are attempting something that would irk her – such as attempting to escape with Aoife – and ensure that the village descends into madness. Siobhan requires a minute to align her mind with that of Sarenya, and always attempts to do so somewhere out of sight, where she is less likely to be interrupted.</span></span></td></tr></tbody></table><h3 data-anchor style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:1rem 0px 0.5rem;padding:0px;font-weight:normal;font-size:1.25em;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-underline-header);color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><br style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\" /></span></span></h3><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;width:622px;border-collapse:collapse;background:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);margin:0.5em 0px;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><tbody style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><tr style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><td style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;padding:0.25em 0px 0.25em 2px\"><h3 data-anchor=\"folklore-of-thess\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0px 0px 0.5rem;padding:0px;font-weight:normal;font-size:1.25em;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-underline-header)\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Folklore of Thess</span></span></h3><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Father of Storms.</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"> While the isles are named after Thess, the principle deity to the people of the region is her husband, Cuwenn – a severe, vengeful storm god. They believe Cuwenn caused the original inhabitants of the isles to be lost at sea as punishment for some forgotten sin. In truth, however, it was Thess that did so, and Cuwenn is an invention of Lady Sarenya. He is often depicted as a man with three eyes and a beard of octopus-like tentacles.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;letter-spacing:normal\"></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;letter-spacing:normal\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Lunar Faces.</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"> Thess is a many-faced goddess. Much like the moon that she is often associated with, she takes many forms – the most prominent among them being the Maiden of Storms and the Tidemother. As the Maiden, Thess is vengeful, stormy, and reckless. As the Tidemother, she is nurturing and steady, and it was as the Tidemother that she took pity on the isles’ first settlers. She raised the isles from the deep for them, and tasked them with manning her mighty lighthouse, using its light to lead lost ships to safety.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;letter-spacing:normal\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Common Knowledge.</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"> Though the exact truths of their own mythology have been lost, the people of Cress are exceptionally pious, and are more than willing to expound on what they know of their ocean gods.</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":500000,"name":"Llyanys","type":"text","_id":"fD0THF61EITZ9TVB","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Nine miles east of Cress is the ghost village of Llanys, a run-down, abandoned settlement nestled between two broad, sloping hills. Much like Saltvine, Llanys was emptied when the population of the isles began to sharply decline, and now its houses – many of them built like warrens into the hills – have been silent for almost a decade.</p><p><strong>The Search</strong>. The former home of Aoife’s uncle, Aedus, can be found here. Aoife vaguely recalls that the entrance was a stone doorway leading into the side of the hills, with a half-moon crescent inscribed upon the keystone atop it. Finding the correct doorway despite the oppressive mist is a DC 16 Wisdom (Perception) check, with each failure causing the characters to wander fruitlessly through the village’s empty remains for an additional half hour.</p><p><strong>On the Clock</strong>. If Aoife is with the characters, Lady Sarenya will at this point have compelled bands of villagers from Cress to scour the island for her. For every two hours that the characters remain in Llanys, a roving band of enthralled villagers (4 Cultists and 3 Berserkers, Basic Rules) will pass through the village. Evading them requires that the characters succeed on a DC 15 Dexterity (Stealth) check.</p><p><strong>Aedus’ Gift</strong>. Once found, the entrance to Aedus’ home leads into the dingy remnants of what once a comfortable – if slightly claustrophobic – three-room dwelling. A successful Intelligence (Investigation) or Wisdom (Perception) check against a DC of 13 uncovers a discoloured patch where the packed earth floor was clearly dug up and resettled some time ago.</p><p>Digging through the cold, hard earth takes ten minutes, and reveals a large, unadorned wooden box. Inside is a map of the island that includes @UUID[.GzTYxcdIwnMVVDAm]{The Wind's Widow}, @UUID[.gYiEhGFJyJPbN8IC]{The Moonstones}, alongside a short letter addressed to Aoife @UUID[JournalEntry.QWA0NNNrhQvE0i6o.JournalEntryPage.UY3TYW83gbljlbXu]{Aedus’ Letter}.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":600000,"name":"The Wind's Widow","type":"text","_id":"GzTYxcdIwnMVVDAm","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The wreckage of the Wind’s Widow, a trading vessel that washed ashore of the Isles of Thess a decade ago, floats just off the southern shoreline of Ulune. Shattered by the battle (@UUID[.7Hlpzx5SvQ1CPg7c#trouble-on-thess]{Trouble on Thess}) that took place when its crew – alongside Aedus – attempted to flee the isles, the dilapidated hulk is held in place by the jagged rocks that jut from the sea in this area.</span></p><blockquote style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px 0.5em 10px;padding:0px 0px 0px 20px;border-left:3px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);font-style:italic;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><em>Read out: “As you crest one of the grassy hills that slope across the island, you reach the edge of a jagged cliff leading down into the frothing sea. Ahead, you can see a dark, slanted shape looming through the mist, jutting up from the water. When you squint, you think you can make out a mast, or a piece of shattered stern – signs that the shape is what remains of a wrecked ship…”</em></span></p></blockquote><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Coastal Cliff</strong>. The wreckage of the Wind’s Widow lies over a hundred feet out to sea, visible at first only as a large, slumped shadow that can be seen through the mist. A trail of large, jutting rocks provides a perilous pathway to the wreck, but getting down to them requires making a 60-ft. climb across a stony, wave-slicked cliff face. Completing this treacherous climb requires a DC 15 Strength (Athletics) check.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"></p><img src=\"worlds/bloodlords-of-the-deep/assets/pages/4oGPNmfFpv6uUHoR-pages-GzTYxcdIwnMVVDAm-image-blPmCubKyOPtkwWO.png\" /><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Aedus’ Corpse</strong>. Aedus’ skeletal corpse is hooked to the wreckage by a long cord of rope (indicated on the above map). Glittering upon a chain of silver, a bronze key hangs about its neck. This key opens the chest in The Moon Key. Finding Aedus’ corpse requires that a character be within 20 ft. of it and succeeds on a DC 15 Intelligence (Investigation) check.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">The Moon Key.</strong> A small, silver-lined chest of smooth elm is wedged between part of the ship’s hull and one of the rocks that spear through it (indicated on the above map). Inside lies a silver talisman in the shape of a crescent moon – the Moon Key. This talisman is a holy symbol of Thess and the only means by which @UUID[.07GxBSG8E1xnBbNO]{The Lighthouse of Thess} can be entered. Finding the chest requires that a character succeeds on a DC 15 Intelligence (Investigation) check within 20 ft. of it.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The chest is warded by a powerful arcane trap. Once each day, when a creature attempts to handle it without knowing the proper arcane words, it releases a wave of thunderous force that ripples through the air for 60 ft. around it and spreads far further through water. Creatures in the area must succeed on a DC 14 Constitution saving throw or be pushed 15 ft. directly away from the chest and stunned until the end of their next turn.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The blast alerts the drowners in Watchers in the Water, which will arrive and attack in 3 rounds.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Watchers in the Water</strong>. Lady Sarenya prefers that the isles’ inhabitants do not attempt to leave the isles, and has stationed three @UUID[JournalEntry.2f3mNI4pjB1Da331.JournalEntryPage.QirWwdeKZEQwcDkH]{Thessidian Drowner} in the nearby waters.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">In combat, the drowners are adept hunters, using their swim speed to outmaneuver and isolate targets. When possible, they will attempt to force the characters into the water, where they have the advantage.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">They are compelled to guard the coast single-mindedly, and will withdraw from combat should the characters retreat halfway up the cliff face, returning to their duties.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Wave of Doom</strong>. When the drowners arrive, they bring with them a massive wave that can be seen building up at a distance. This wave smashes ove the hulk of the Wind’s Widow within 3 rounds of the trap in The Moon Key being triggered. Characters within 160 ft. of the Wind’s Widow must succeed on a DC 20 Strength saving throw or be hurled 40 ft. toward the cliff face.</span></p><p><br class=\"Apple-interchange-newline\" /></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":700000,"name":"The Moonstones","type":"text","_id":"gYiEhGFJyJPbN8IC","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Six miles north of Llanys lies the Circle of the Moon, an ancient ritual site and the resting place of the goddess Thess’ own spear. No creature has been able to recover the spear since time immemorial. Thess may be gone, but a shred of her power remains, protecting the spear from unnatural creatures like Lady Sarenya.</span></p><blockquote style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px 0.5em 10px;padding:0px 0px 0px 20px;border-left:3px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);font-style:italic;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><em>Read out: “Materializing from the mist up ahead, you at first spy a series of long, thin shadows standing in a huddled circle. As you get closer, it becomes apparent that they are a semicircle of tall, dark stone pillars.”</em></span></p></blockquote><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Deep Mists</strong>. The Moonstones are located in the deep mists, and all @UUID[.7Hlpzx5SvQ1CPg7c]{their effects} apply to the area.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Deathless Guardians.</strong> Though Sarenya has never been able to unearth and attune to the spear sealed below, she found a way to harness some of its power, using it to bend the mists of the isles to her command. As such, the area is heavily guarded by her servants. After the characters find the Circle, they have only one minute (real time) to inspect it before its defenders attack.</span></p><img src=\"https://imgsrv.roll20.net/?src=https%3A//cdn.discordapp.com/attachments/872251721718595596/1006038228123521114/The-Moonstones-NightR2.jpg\" /><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Four @UUID[JournalEntry.2f3mNI4pjB1Da331.JournalEntryPage.iH9J4uUznmCJVzby]{Thessidian Vampire} lurk in the mists, keeping their distance and using their Haunting Song in sequence to draw the characters away from another and sow discord. They will only engage sufficiently isolated characters personally, and when in danger will use their Misty Retreat to escape. They have a handful of enthralled villagers (4 Cultists and 4 Berserkers, Basic Rules) under their command, and will use them as disposable chaff to occupy the characters and whittle them down, sending them ahead.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Phases of the Moon</strong>. Each of the stone pillars that stand in a semi-circle around the central dais has a top section with eight segmented facings. Upon each facing is a symbol representing @UUID[JournalEntry.QWA0NNNrhQvE0i6o.JournalEntryPage.1nLat9o2T4Tsy5y9]{one of the phases of the moon}.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">These top sections can be turned so that different symbols face toward the centre of the circle. In order to unearth Thess’ spear, the pillars must be configured according to the sequence on the map above.<br style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\" />Whenever a facing is placed correctly, a brilliant pillar of white light spears up from the top of that stone, shedding 10 ft. of daylight around it.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Spear of the Goddess.</strong> When the pillars are properly configured, the earth rumbles, and a brilliant flash of pale white light washes over the area, extending in a 60-ft. radius from the centre of the circle and lasting for 1 hour. This light is treated as daylight.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The central dais splits apart, grinding open to reveal a crumbling spiral staircase into the dark below.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Just 60 ft. down, at the end of the staircase, is a circular altar upon which the @UUID[Item.p2QWLnS66byB4SJ1]{Stormspear of Thess} is impaled, its tip sunk deep into the stone.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Losing Control.</strong> The arcane connection to Thess’ spear that Lady Sarenya has forged over many years of study is how she exerts her will over the mists of the isles, and the minds of its inhabitants. Should the spear be removed, that connection is broken. The villagers under her sway immediately fall unconscious, awakening eight hours later with fractured memories of the last several hours.</span></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":900000,"name":"The Lighthouse of Thess","type":"text","_id":"07GxBSG8E1xnBbNO","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">A relic of a lost age, the Lighthouse of Thess is an ancient, monolithic structure that rises up from the eastern peninsula of Ulune, its shadow clearly visible through the mist.<br style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\" /></span></p><blockquote style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px 0.5em 10px;padding:0px 0px 0px 20px;border-left:3px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);font-style:italic;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><em>Read out: “The peninsula ahead turns inward at its tip, jagged cliff walls forming a steep cove. At its rear, an immense, dark form spears upward into the sky, disappearing into the mist – a tower so vast that it defies imagination, its shadow cutting across the mist like the blade of a sword. Around its base, a waterfall spills into the cove, tumbling down toward a thin strip of land leading up to the tower.”</em></span></p></blockquote><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The lighthouse was once the centre of Thess’ worship, bustling with petitioners and clerics, the immense brazier at its top guiding lost seafarers to safe harbour. Nowadays, the lighthouse has stood abandoned for as long as anyone on the isles can remember, the arcane mechanisms necessary to enter it having been long lost.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Impossible Construction</strong>. The Lighthouse of Thess was built during a lost age of wonder. The dark, glistening stone it is constructed from is seemingly impervious to harm, and impossible to pass through by magical means.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Cliffside Passage.</strong> The Lighthouse of Thess rises up from the middle of a steep, rocky cove. Along the western side of this cove, a winding set of stone steps leads down to a thin strip of rocky beach. From here, a thin spit of land surrounded by jagged rocks is visible, tapering through the middle of the cove and leading up to the lighthouse.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Waterfall Entry</strong>. An immense waterfall rushes over the top of the cove, its waters running around the main body of the lighthouse tower and tumbling down into the sea below.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The Stormbringer Leviathan can pass through the waters undeterred, as it is a divine servant of Thess.<br style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\" />[MAP - Waterfall]</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Beyond the waterfall is a large cavern that extends 45 ft. into the cove walls, is 50-ft. tall, and is 65-ft. wide. The immense, black stone base of the lighthouse is merged into the rock wall opposite the falls. Its surface is featureless save for a tall, 40-ft.- wide set of stone doors that are impossible to open by any mundane or magical means save @UUID[Item.4Fux45QTDbxytGzI]{The Moon Key}.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The doors feature carved depictions of Thess’ two aspects, the Maiden of Storms and the Tidemother.</span></p><blockquote style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px 0.5em 10px;padding:0px 0px 0px 20px;border-left:3px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);font-style:italic;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><em>Read out: “Upon the stone are carved images of two tall, stern-featured women with long fish-like lower bodies and billowing wings resembling betta fish fins. One has wild hair surrounded by bolts of lightning, while the other has flowing hair and a halo behind her head.”</em></span></p></blockquote><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Where their hands meet in the centre of the doorway, there is a crescent-shaped niche that the Moon Key can be inserted into, causing the doors to grind open and reveal a long, dark hallway leading into the lighthouse’s innards.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Lair of the Leviathan</strong>. The cavern hidden beneath the waterfall is the resting place of the Stormbringer Leviathan that was previously used to attack the Fairy Queen. When a creature that is not one of Lady Sarenya’s minions approaches within 10 ft. of the falls, the monster emerges and attacks, fighting to the death to prevent their entry.</span></p><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;width:622px;border-collapse:collapse;background:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);margin:0.5em 0px;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><tbody style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><tr style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><td style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;padding:0.25em 0px 0.25em 2px\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;color:rgb(231, 99, 99)\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">! God-Fearing Beast. The leviathan may have been corrupted by Sarenya, but it still reacts with awe and fear to the Stormspear of Thess. The leviathan will not move within 10 ft. of a character carrying the spear, and attacks them with disadvantage. Additionally, the spear ignores the leviathan’s damage resistances.</span></span></td></tr></tbody></table><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Enchanted Frog.</strong> If by the time the characters make their way to the Lighthouse of Thess it has been more than three hours since they arrived at the isles, Plo’orgk will be waiting for them near the Cliffside Passage. By now, Plo’orgk’s search party has been ambushed and incapacited by Lady Sarenya’s minions, and the frogman has been enthralled under Sarenya’s psychic control.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Plo’orgk approaches the characters while feigning caution, and tells them that his fellow crewmen have been captured. He will report having escaped, and watching a pair of vampires lead their captives through the waterfall below, telling them that in order to pass through, they had to approach it in single file.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">This is an utter fabrication. He is being compelled to lead the characters into a trap – should the characters follow his instructions, the leviathan uses its Water Spear before revealing itself and attacking, taking advantage of the characters’ formation in a straight line to employ the ability to maximum effect. At this point, Plo’orgk becomes actively hostile, and attempts to distance himself and attack the characters from afar.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Whenever Plo’orgk takes damage, he may make a Wisdom saving throw against the effect controlling his mind (DC 15). Should he succeed, he frees himself from Sarenya’s control, but the mental strain makes him dizzy and entirely useless in combat, prompting him to return to the Fairy Queen.</span></p><h3 data-anchor=\"into-the-lighthouse.\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:1rem 0px 0.5rem;padding:0px;font-weight:normal;font-size:1.25em;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-underline-header);color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Into the Lighthouse</span></h3><blockquote style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px 0.5em 10px;padding:0px 0px 0px 20px;border-left:3px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);font-style:italic;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><em>Read out: “Beyond its stone gates, there is a broad, arched corridor leading into the lighthouse. The smooth, dark stone walls are decorated with flowing, abstract carvings, vaguely reminiscent both of waves and of constellations.<br style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\" />Eventually, the corridor opens out into a cavernous central chamber at what must be the base of the lighthouse – an immense circular room with walls that stretch so high that they disappear well out of any torchlight. Gigantic stone steps spiral up along the walls to the ancient lantern room high above, but time has made them virtually useless, gaps as wide as sixty feet having formed by breakages in the stone.”</em></span></p></blockquote><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">A perfectly smooth pillar of featureless black stone rises from the centre of the chamber, supporting the lantern room above. Around it is a 10-ft.-wide opening in the floor, with steps spiraling down into the dark under the lighthouse (The Dark Below, pg.x), winding their way around the central pillar.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Moonfire.</strong> The lantern room itself is a vast domed chamber with a huge, 30-ft.-wide silver brazier dominating its centre. It has lain cold and empty for generations, but, with some prodigious effort, a band of powerful mortals might be capable of lighting its fire once more – if only for a short time.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">At each cardinal direction on the brazier’s rim is a large, swirling rune. Should a character with spellcasting ability touch any of them, they can feel something tugging at them. A successful DC 15 (Intelligence) Arcana or Wisdom (Religion) check reveals that a character can drain the energy of up to 4 levels of spells into the brazier (in any configuration – i.e. a character could spend four level 1 spell slots, one level 4 spell slot, etc).</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Doing so causes the brazier to fill with majestic, silvery fire – a flame visible half the world away. The light of this fire causes nearby creatures to be instantly cleansed of any poisons, diseases, or exhaustion.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Divine Reward. A small morsel of Thess’ divine power still lingers in the Lighthouse of Thess. Should the characters light the brazier in Moonfire, a flickering aspect of the goddess appears before them:</span></p><blockquote style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px 0.5em 10px;padding:0px 0px 0px 20px;border-left:3px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);font-style:italic;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><em>Read out: “The flame parts like a pair of cresting waves, and from them steps a pale, ghostly woman, her hair roiling like stormclouds and her eyes flashing with lightning. Glistening fish-scale robes billow from her half-visible body, and around her head shines the light of the moon. Her lips move, but from them comes only the sound of gentle waves lapping at stony shores, and she holds out her hand to you. In her grasp hangs a heavy, spherical lantern of shining silver.”</em></span></p></blockquote><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The lantern is the @UUID[Item.9UrOoqa75MxebeyN]{Lantern of Thess}. Should the characters take it, the apparition fades, leaving behind only the sound of distant waves. If the characters do not take the lantern after one minute, the vision recedes back into the flame and disappears.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"></p><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;width:622px;border-collapse:collapse;background:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);margin:0.5em 0px;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><tbody style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><tr style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><td style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;padding:0.25em 0px 0.25em 2px\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;color:rgb(231, 99, 99)\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">! It’s Dangerous to Go Alone... If Aoife has accompanied the characters to this point, she will go no further, admitting that she would only be a burden in any kind of climactic battle. She will, however, hand her Wardstone over to the characters, and will remain at the base of the lighthouse to pray for the party’s success.</span></span></td></tr></tbody></table>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":800000,"name":"The Temple of Thess","type":"text","_id":"9jNtSCsH2BGHNOx3","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Far to the north of Ulune, the ancient Temple of Thess stands. Its stones remain strong despite the ages, but a sinister corruption festers in its halls. For centuries now, the Temple of Thess has served as a mouthpiece for Lady Sarenya and a base of operations for her minions, many of its priestesses having been changed over the years into the ancient vampire’s spawn.</span></p><blockquote style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px 0.5em 10px;padding:0px 0px 0px 20px;border-left:3px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);font-style:italic;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><em>Read out: “Looming out of the mist ahead is a large, white stone building, its arched rooftop encrusted with bright twisting veins of bright coral. Broad stone steps lead up to a set of sturdy oaken doors at its front. On either side sits a smaller, humbler wooden dwelling, their rooftops covered with thatchwork.”</em></span></p></blockquote><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Lantern Houses</strong>. The two small buildings to either side of the temple act as storehouses and sleeping quarters for young Thessidines, and their interiors are austere and cold. They are stocked with rows of lanterns and plentiful supplies of moonweed lighter, but no priestesses are currently present.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">The Temple.</strong> The Temple interior is a spacious hall cut from immaculate white stone, flanked by a pair of adjoining chambers where Thessidines sometimes pray. The main hall that characters would enter immediately upon walking into the temple is dominated by a large pool of clear water running through its centre (which priestesses use to ritually wash themselves before performing religious duties).</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">On the far side of the hall is a small set of steps leading to a smaller room in which there is a ritual pool used in rare circumstances to enact holy drownings – a religious ceremony in which priestesses are brought to the edge of drowning to bring them closer to Thess and grant them visions of the goddess’ will.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Secret Ways.</strong> The drowning pool at the back of the temple is only 5 ft. deep, but beneath its waters is a secret opening. 5 ft. wide, the opening leads 15 ft. down through a narrow tunnel before leading into a small subterranean pool. This pool is located in a small cavern, and a narrow opening in the rock leads down into the tunnel in @UUID[JournalEntry.98SzEQ7twwSI37nR.JournalEntryPage.RYnPla84RLNxr4ts]{Beneath the Temple}.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Additionally, under the 10-ft. deep cleansing pool in the centre of the temple, there is a 40-ft. radius flooded edifice that extends beneath the floor, centered on the pool. Three @UUID[JournalEntry.2f3mNI4pjB1Da331.JournalEntryPage.QirWwdeKZEQwcDkH]{Thessidian Drowner} wait there, and should a battle begin above, the vampiric priestesses will call upon their aid. They will prioritize dragging characters down into the water with them.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Corrupted Clergy</strong>. There are five senior priestesses attending to their duties inside the temple – all of whom are vampires (currently disguised as humans). Three are @UUID[JournalEntry.2f3mNI4pjB1Da331.JournalEntryPage.iH9J4uUznmCJVzby]{Thessidian Vampire}, while two are @UUID[JournalEntry.2f3mNI4pjB1Da331.JournalEntryPage.7ocFru77Y2Z9oKbE]{Thessidian Ancient}. In addition, two sworn guardians – men selected for their piety, and brainwashed by Sarenya into obeying her and her minions’ every command – stand watch near the doors, reading and willing to defend the clergy. They wear gleaming, pearl-like plate armour and use the Knight statistics (Basic Rules).</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">One of the Ancients – a woman called @UUID[JournalEntry.qJg4GYQDMSUG8Wxt.JournalEntryPage.00GvYiWAEsM7dJkc]{Dairine} who appears in human form as a slender maiden with long dark hair, pale skin, and dim blue eyes – will humour any of the characters’ questions, but insist that nothing is amiss.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The vampires will only attack if the characters attempt to thoroughly investigate the temple.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">False Sanctuary.</strong> If the villagers of Cress have been driven into madness by Sarenya by the time the characters reach the temple, the clergy will offer to shelter them inside. In reality they intend on simply wasting the characters’ time, keeping them secured until Errol and Flynn are both dead.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">They also reinforce their numbers during this time, ensuring that they can keep the characters detained by force if necessary. For every hour that the characters remain in the temple, another Thessidian Vampire is psychically called to it, up to a maximum of three additional vampires. If there are any of their reinforcements present when the characters attempt to leave, the vampires will attack.</span></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.288","createdTime":1665945916885,"modifiedTime":1665976468849,"lastModifiedBy":"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L"},"_id":"4oGPNmfFpv6uUHoR","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L":3}}
{"name":"Part III - The Elder One","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Beneath the Temple","type":"text","_id":"RYnPla84RLNxr4ts","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<img src=\"modules/bloodlords-of-the-deep/journal/000_-_Bloodlords_of_the_Deep/003_-_Part_III_-_The_Elder_One/000_-_Beneath_the_Temple/avatar.png\" /><p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">In this section, the characters delve into the subterranean warrens that criss-cross beneath the Isles of Thess, and confront Lady Sarenya in her place of power.</span></p><h3 data-anchor=\"beneath-the-temple\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:1rem 0px 0.5rem;padding:0px;font-weight:normal;font-size:1.25em;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-underline-header);color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Beneath the Temple</span></h3><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The passage leading beneath The Temple of Thess winds deep into the crust of the island. The air is humid and close, and the passage walls are of a moist, rough stone. The passage twists and turns for almost half an hour at a casual walking pace, eventually opening out into a large, rocky cave room with veins of coral criss-crossing along its walls.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">There are two exits – one to the left of the entrance, leading into a long corridor where faint traceries of coral trace lines through the rock, and one to the right, leading into a passage cut from smooth stone. The leftmost passage leads into the @UUID[.u6OIZqgoiA2w2Ec0]{Sanctum of the Deep}, while the rightmost passage leads to the sealed, sheer stone door to the area described in Beneath the Lighthouse.</span></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Beneath the Lighthouse","type":"text","_id":"TfrB46iYC63Nzq0F","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The spiral staircase at the base of the Lighthouse of Thess leads deep below the isles. They wind their way down for just over 300 ft., the smooth stone walls decorated with carvings that depict the secret history of the isles – and events not yet to come.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Prophecies of Old. </strong>Who carved the glyphs and simplistic, stylized images that line the walls of the stairway is a mystery lost to time, but they tell a step-by-step story that begins in the isles’ distant past and culminates in the near future:</span></p><blockquote style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px 0.5em 10px;padding:0px 0px 0px 20px;border-left:3px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);font-style:italic;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><em>Read out: “The carvings begin by depicting a woman surrounded by lines of gold, raising the isles from the deep and guiding a fleet of ships to them. Her face has two evenly split halves – one with hair the colour of the moon, and one with hair like stormclouds. They show other golden figures leaving the world, passing into the clouds, and the first figure refusing to follow them. The next set of carvings shows her growing gradually smaller, the golden lines around her growing thinner and thinner.<br style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\" />Then, they depict the arrival of a three-eyed beast from the stars, and its battle with the golden woman. The creature is shown bound in a coral prison, and the golden woman is depicted with only one line of gold still emanating out of her, and passing it to a group of smaller figures before disappearing entirely.<br style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\" />The passage of time is indicated by moon cycle after moon cycle, until, at the end of the stairway, a pair of almost identical male figures appear. Gold lines crown their heads, and one has moon-like hair, while the other has hair like stormy clouds. They are depicted holding a spear aloft, light radiating out of it, and shadows fleeing around them.”</em></span></p></blockquote><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Paths Below.</strong> At the bottom of the stairway, there is a plain, domed chamber with a single exit – a narrow corridor with smooth stone walls. This corridor extends for 60 ft. before terminating at a featureless stone door. This entryway is warded with powerful abjuration magic that has kept Sarenya from entering for generations, and has no visible lock, but presenting the Moon Key or the Stormspear of Thess causes it to rumble open. The passage beyond leads into the chamber described in Beneath the Temple.</span></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Sanctum of the Deep","type":"text","_id":"u6OIZqgoiA2w2Ec0","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">An edifice as ancient as the isles themselves, the Sanctum of the Deep once served as the final resting place for the most devoted of Thess’ followers. It is also where the Elder One was imprisoned in enchanted coral – and where the eldritch abomination still dwells. The tombs of old have long been despoiled and emptied, Lady Sarenya having defiled this sacred ground and taken it as her lair.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Bones of Old</strong>. The path leading to the Sanctum of the Deep is a narrow stone corridor, traces of coral forming natural shelves that line the walls. These shelves house the ancient skulls of countless past worshippers, though they are in grave disrepair and have clearly not been properly cleaned or maintained in some time.<br style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\" /><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">The Sanctum.</strong></span></p><blockquote style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px 0.5em 10px;padding:0px 0px 0px 20px;border-left:3px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);font-style:italic;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><em>Read out: “The corridor opens into a large, cavernous room, heavy stalactites drooping from its natural stone ceiling. The chamber’s floor consists of raised stone platforms that run over a pool of murky, deep water. An eerie, pulsing light emanates from somewhere deep below, casting rippling caustics across the rocky walls of the chamber.”</em></span></p></blockquote><p></p><img src=\"https://imgsrv.roll20.net/?src=https%3A//cdn.discordapp.com/attachments/872251721718595596/1006045670098075668/The-Moonstones-NightR20.jpg\" /><p><strong>Placement. Errol (E), Flynn (F), Vampires (V1, V2), Lady Sarenya (S), Ancient (A1, A2).</strong></p><p></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Offerings.</strong> On the far end of the room, where a large portion of the flooring has crumbled, Errol and Flynn Athersern stand on opposite sides of a circular opening in the floor (positions indicated above). They are deep in a hypnotic trance, entirely unaware of their surroundings, and a Thessidian Vampire loiters beside each of them, ensuring that they do not unexpectedly break free of Lady Sarenya’s control.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The Athersens cannot be roused from Sarenya’s control by simple damage at this point.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Both Athersens have three levels of exhaustion and 20 remaining hit points.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Unseen Threats</strong>. 20 ft. below the water’s surface, at positions indicated on the above map, @UUID[JournalEntry.2f3mNI4pjB1Da331.JournalEntryPage.LBIL03FeGRrXTSVU]{Lady Sarenya} and two @UUID[JournalEntry.2f3mNI4pjB1Da331.JournalEntryPage.7ocFru77Y2Z9oKbE]{Thessidian Ancient} wait in silence, psychically communing with the Elder One. Should the characters at any point move within 40 ft. of any of them, they instantly sense the unwanted presence, and rise to the surface to ensure that the Athersern twins are not stolen from them.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Lady Sarenya and her minions have no scruples about killing the characters on the spot, but the ancient vampire is also not averse to negotiation. If her Probing Telepathy ability unveils any points of leverage or weakness in any of the characters, she will attempt to sway them to her side, often making promises that she will not – or cannot – in reality uphold.</span></p><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;width:622px;border-collapse:collapse;background:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);margin:0.5em 0px;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><tbody style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><tr style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><td style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;padding:0.25em 0px 0.25em 2px\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;color:rgb(231, 99, 99)\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">! Common Ground. One exception to Sarenya’s overall duplicitous nature is that she has a genuine empathy for creatures who, like she once was, are facing death or debilitation by illness. If she learns that one of the characters or their loved ones are in similar circumstances, she will offer to free them from this fate via vampirism – and she will uphold this promise.</span></span></td></tr></tbody></table><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Desperate Measures.</strong> Lady Sarenya has limited time in which to offer the Athersens to her master. The allotted time for this sacrifice is near, but has not yet arrived. Should it seem as though the characters are getting uncomfortably close to either of the Athersens, she will telepathically order the two vampires present to slit the twins’ throats and let their blood flow into the water – or, if she has the opportunity, will do it herself.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">For the purposes of this combat, this action immediately reduces one of the twins to 0 hit points.</span></p><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;width:622px;border-collapse:collapse;background:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);margin:0.5em 0px;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><tbody style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><tr style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><td style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;padding:0.25em 0px 0.25em 2px\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;color:rgb(231, 99, 99)\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">! Blood in the Water. When reduced to 0 hit points, the Athersens should be treated as player characters and given death saving throws, as well as the ability to be stabilized by all normal means.</span></span></td></tr></tbody></table><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">After being reduced to 0 hit points and revived or stabilized, the Athersen twins break free of Lady Sarenya’s control.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Power of Thess</strong>. Should the Athersen twins come into contact with one another, they immediately regain their full hit point total and lose any levels of exhaustion they are suffering from, and awaken from their fugue state. Should the two of them grasp the Stormspear of Thess at once, they immediately attune to it, a 10-ft. aura of bright light surrounding them. While they hold the spear, it does not run out of charges.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">An Ancient Evil Arises.</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"> @UUID[JournalEntry.2f3mNI4pjB1Da331.JournalEntryPage.pbNhLrUVB6Upu4cL]{The Elder One} lurks deep below the water, awaiting the dual sacrifice of the Athersens to replenish its power. Five rounds after either Athersen is reduced to 0 hit points, it emerges from the central hole that the Athersens are arranged beside and attempts to deal with the characters itself.<br style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\" />From this point, the Elder One is capable of using all the Aboleth (Basic Rules) lair actions, and does so.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Evil Prevails</strong>. The moment either of the Atherserns is felled and their blood touches the water, the Elder One begins feeding upon them. If both Athersern twins die, the Elder One is instantly restored to full power and rises from the depths surrounded in a halo of mind-bending psionic light.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">In this terrible event, the Elder One gains immunity to slashing, bludgeoning, and piercing damage from non-magical weapons and weapons with a magical bonus of +2 or lower, as well as immunity to damage dealt by spells of 3rd level or lower.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Surely, the characters are doomed.</span></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":400000,"name":"Conclusion","type":"text","_id":"nXu3fcrdjIzmFxGb","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>In the aftermath of the battle with Lady Sarenya and the Elder One – assuming the characters are able to defeat them – the isles are free for the first time in generations from the grip of evil. The psychic backlash of the Elder One’s death causes some brief confusion among the isles’ inhabitants, but their minds clear soon after, and some even begin to experience the reemergence of memories locked away by Sarenya’s conditioning – such as the events surrounding the Wind’s Widow.</p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">The Fire Rekindled</strong>. If the Moon Key has been retrieved, Errol and Flynn will use their shared power to reignite the brazier atop the Lighthouse of Thess. For generations to come, its light will continue to guide sailors to safety.</p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Errol</strong>. Should he survive, Errol is grateful to be alive and to see his home restored to a state far better than the one he left it in. He wishes to stay briefly on the isles, but within him is the stormy, restless aspect of Thess, and he does not intend on staying long. He will pay the characters what they are due, and will make an oath that if they are ever in need of a ship, the Fairy Queen will always take them as passengers.</p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Flynn</strong>. Should he survive, Flynn declares that he is forever in the characters’ debt, and though somewhat confused after his engineered disappearance, is ecstatic to learn the secret history they have begun to uncover. He will arrange a humble feast in the characters’ honour, and reward each of them for their efforts with a @UUID[Item.wyYHOGW9NmChNXSr]{Cloak of Scales}</p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><br style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\" /></span></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.288","createdTime":1665946067157,"modifiedTime":1665976468859,"lastModifiedBy":"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L"},"_id":"98SzEQ7twwSI37nR","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L":3}}
{"name":"Appendix A - DM Shortcut","flags":{"R20Converter":{"handout-order":0,"handout-archived":false},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.bloodlords-of-the-deep.journal.YzdlNDY4ZDQxOWMz"}},"pages":[{"name":"DM Shortcut","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://imgsrv.roll20.net/?src=https%3A//cdn.discordapp.com/attachments/872251721718595596/1006049087080120450/DM_Shortcut.jpg\" /><br /></p>"},"_id":"8pAkIrRGLqYFY9qz","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.288","createdTime":1665862301154,"modifiedTime":1665976468860,"lastModifiedBy":"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L"},"_id":"QEhWoQH7bANgmg9B","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L":3}}
{"name":"Appendix E - Handouts","flags":{"R20Converter":{"handout-order":0,"handout-archived":false},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.bloodlords-of-the-deep.journal.NDJmZTRkY2QwZTM5"}},"pages":[{"name":"Aedus’ Letter","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<blockquote><p>To my dearest niece, </p><p>In truth, it is my wish that this letter never be opened. Should I fail tonight, however, the fate of the isles will fall to you, and the knowledge I have accrued must also be passed on. </p><p>For centuries, our people have lived a lie. The high priestess of the Temple of Thess is not what she seems – long ago, she pledged herself to a dark power that dwells beneath the isles. This creature is the true face of Cuwenn, a false god propped up by its servants among us. It drinks up our prayers and our dreams, subsisting upon us, awaiting the day that your father’s bloodline grows strong enough that it can feast on the power he holds and rise again. That day must not come.</p><p>A ship has washed ashore by the name of the Wind’s Widow. I intend on fleeing the isles aboard it, to bring back your uncle Errol. Together, he and Flynn can defeat the abomination beneath the isles. I take with me a relic of our beloved isles’ past, a talisman that opens the old lighthouse upon the eastern peninsula. Within is a secret way into the lair of our enemy.</p><p>Enclosed beside this letter is a map. I have marked on it the Wind’s Widow’s landing, as well as an old place of power where an artifact of Thess’ time lies buried – one that our enemy covets greatly, and uses to spread their power over the isles, numbing our minds with the mist. Sarenya and her minions will no doubt try to prevent my escape, and by the time this letter reaches you, it is likely that much of what happens tonight will be erased from memory. </p><p>But should I have failed, you must continue my work. You must find a way.\"<br /></p></blockquote>"},"_id":"UY3TYW83gbljlbXu","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":100000,"name":"Moonstone Cycle","type":"text","_id":"1nLat9o2T4Tsy5y9","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<img src=\"https://imgsrv.roll20.net/?src=https%3A//cdn.discordapp.com/attachments/872251721718595596/1006049093509980191/Moon_Cut_Out.jpg\" />","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.288","createdTime":1665862301120,"modifiedTime":1665976468861,"lastModifiedBy":"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L"},"_id":"QWA0NNNrhQvE0i6o","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L":3}}
{"name":"Appendix D - Region Maps","flags":{"R20Converter":{"handout-order":0,"handout-archived":false},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.bloodlords-of-the-deep.journal.N2M4MjZjOTcyOTcw"}},"pages":[{"name":"Region Maps","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><img src=\"https://imgsrv.roll20.net/?src=https%3A//cdn.discordapp.com/attachments/872251721718595596/1006049708332040282/Map_Version_2HO.png\" /><br /></p>\n<section class=\"secret\"><p>GM Notes : </p><p><img src=\"https://imgsrv.roll20.net/?src=https%3A//cdn.discordapp.com/attachments/872251721718595596/1006049684483211264/MapHO.png\" /><br /></p></section>"},"_id":"tiQqTvtALWhMHbHV","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.288","createdTime":1665862301117,"modifiedTime":1665976468861,"lastModifiedBy":"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L"},"_id":"dAn1O1lAONlZbkHC","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L":3}}
{"name":"Part I - The Voyage","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"The Hook","type":"text","_id":"sqpGk80iTUnOijUx","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<img src=\"modules/bloodlords-of-the-deep/journal/000_-_Bloodlords_of_the_Deep/001_-_Part_I_-_The_Voyage/000_-_The_Hook/avatar.png\" /><p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">In this section, the characters meet the crew o</span>f @UUID[.tUav8JS45ru0tO8Y]{The Fairy Queen}, tr<span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">averse the seas to the Isles of Thess, and are ambushed by the servants of Lady Sarenya.</span></p><h3><strong>The Hook</strong></h3><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The characters have been contacted by a noted ship captain by the name of @UUID[JournalEntry.2f3mNI4pjB1Da331.JournalEntryPage.rgevuWe0ngfwlZhN]{Errol Athersen}. The captain hails from the legendary Isles of Thess, and has been plagued by surreal nightmares of late that make him fear for the fate of his family and their home. He is willing to pay the characters 2,000 gp each to travel on his ship to the misted isles and ensure that his kin are in good health – and will even pay them the full fee if it turns out that nothing is amiss.</span></p><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;width:628px;border-collapse:collapse;background:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);margin:0.5em 0px;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><tbody style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><tr style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><td style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;padding:0.25em 0px 0.25em 2px\"><span style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;color:rgb(231, 99, 99)\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">! Tricksome Seafolk. If the characters are uninterested in contract work, this adventure can be easily inserted any time they might need to travel by ship – in this instance, Errol could simply offer a cheap passage on his vessel and pretend to be sent off-course or lost at sea, intending on forcing the characters’ hands by stranding them on the Isles of Thess.</span></span></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br class=\"Apple-interchange-newline\" /></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"The Fairy Queen","type":"text","_id":"tUav8JS45ru0tO8Y","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>The Fairy Queen is a small, two-masted clipper ship, designed to outpace blockades and evade pursuit by sheer speed and nimbleness alone. A dark wooden cutting of an imperious elvish woman adorns the ship’s prow, serving as its figurehead. The Fairy Queen has served as Errol Athersen’s vessel for well over a decade, and its storied hull is pockmarked with signs of continual wear and repair.</p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>Motley Crew.</strong></span> The crew of the Fairy Queen are cobbled together from across all reaches of the world – some are career sailors, some are misfits driven into the seas by debt or worse, and others are adventurous types that relish the thrill of exploration. All are fiercely loyal to Captain Errol, who seems to have a knack for finding people in their hour of need. If asked, most crewmembers will say that they stay with Errol because he has an uncanny ability to sense the moods of the sea.</p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>Darceri’s Games</strong></span>. First mate of the Fairy Queen, @UUID[JournalEntry.qJg4GYQDMSUG8Wxt.JournalEntryPage.zBNi8V2aDllXRiKn]{Trianna Darceri} is Errol’s most trusted confidant. She is a habitual gambler, and if the characters attempt to pry at her for information on her captain or the Isles of Thess, she will answer their questions only over a game of Black Spot, an old card game popular among sailors.</p><p>Black Spot has three rounds. For each round, the winner is decided by a contested Charisma (Deception) check. Darceri will insist on a bet of at least 100 gp.</p><p>For each round of Black Spot a character plays, roll a 1d6 and consult the following table to determine what information Darceri hands out:</p><p></p><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\"><tbody><tr><td><p>d6 roll</p></td><td><p>Darceri's Tales</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>“Captain once told me they worship not only Thess the Tidemother on the Isles, but a strange god of storms called Cuwenn. I ain’t ever heard of such a deity, myself, not all the world over.”</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>“I’ve been sailing alongside the captain some thirteen years, and he’s been on the seas longer. And lemme tell you – he ain’t aged a day in all that time.”</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>“You’ve seen the captain cast little magic tricks, no? Once I asked a mage down by the Red Coast what manner of magic that was, and he said it certainly weren’t no wizardry like his own.”</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>“They say that long ago, there were a lighthouse on the isles that could be seen from half the world away. Some say it’d lure in ships like moths to a flame, wreck ‘em on the isles’ shores, but some others think it guided the lost safely home. I’d bet it’s nothing but a wreck, now.”</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>“Captain once told me they reckoned his bloodline special on the isles, holy somehow. The way he always knows the wind, I’d believe it too…”</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>“Way the captain tells it, the isles are nothing but hanging mist, sloping hills, and disheartened folk as far as the eye can see. I can quite well imagine why he left.”</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>Way of the Frog</strong></span>. The crew’s tracker, ,@UUID[JournalEntry.2f3mNI4pjB1Da331.JournalEntryPage.ogn7rP5kC4v8xfE5]{Plo'orgk} often lounges in the sun near the ship’s prow. The strange frogman keeps to himself, and occasionally uses a corded spear to fish for meals. He is willing to show inquisitive characters how to fish for aquatic game, however, and will reward particularly skilled students with a @UUID[Item.88WGeXlMcC36waKy]{Deep-Eel Tongue} he harvested recently.</p><p>To earn Plo’orgk’s favour, a character must succeed at catching an impressive haul by making a successful Javelin attack against an AC of 15, then succeeding on a DC 18 Strength (Athletics) check to reel in their kill.</p><p>A character that succeeds in this test also gains Proficiency in Javelins from Plo’orgk’s teachings.</p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>Dreams of Drowning.</strong></span> Once they are aboard his ship, Errol is willing to expand somewhat on his nightmares. He reveals that he has a twin brother –@UUID[JournalEntry.2f3mNI4pjB1Da331.JournalEntryPage.s3scgj3piJ12dYZC]{Flynn Athersen} – that remained on the Isles of Thess. The two have always had magic in their blood, and shared a strange bond that connects them through dreams. Recently, Errol has had vivid, continual nightmares from Flynn’s perspective, in which his brother is being dragged down beneath dark waters.</p><p></p><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\"><tbody><tr><td><p></p><h3>Psychic Lure</h3><p>Errol is correct about one thing – his dreams are indeed ill omens. What he is unaware of, however, is that they are entirely fabricated.</p><p></p><p>Having become aware that she needs both the Athersen twins intact to unleash her dark master from his prison, Lady Sarenya has used her mental powers to put Flynn under a nightmarish trance. She is intentionally broadcasting these horrific visions into Errol’s dreams, using their connection to lure the captain back to his old home.</p><p>Through her power over Flynn, Lady Sarenya can sense Errol’s approach, and is preparing a trap for the prodigal Athersern brother.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Dark Waters","type":"text","_id":"0JSU5LDX5MDtQHrU","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>The voyage to the Isles of Thess is a six-day journey northeast, over an increasingly cold sea. The crew of the Fairy Queen becomes more and more on-edge as the voyale progresses, having heard many strange rumours regarding the shrouded isles.</p><p>Sailors will freely tell the characters that the isles are supposedly impossible to land safely upon save by those who have been there, and that the mist surrounding it is haunted by the lost souls of those that have tried and failed to reach its shores.</p><p>By the third day, the Fairy Queen is plunging through a near-impenetrable mist, and Errol takes the helm, steering the vessel with his eyes closed, relying on his uncanny sense for the sea to navigate.</p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>Darkening Mood</strong></span>. From the third day onward, Errol’s mood begins to sour and he starts to sleep less and less, spending much of his time at the helm, a determined, cold fire entering his expression. As the mist closes in, he begins to navigate with his eyes closed.</p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>Hideous Dreams</strong></span>. After the third day at sea, spellcasters and characters with ki points begin to experience surreal, nightmarish dreams during their sleep. These dreams often fixate upon water, and feature the feeling of clammy, cold limbs brushing against their own.</p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>Crown of Cuwenn (Skill Challenge)</strong></span>. Midway through the fourth day of travel, the ship lurches to one side as Errol steers it away from a massive, jagged rock that rises like a spear out of the mist. He shouts for all hands to be on deck, declaring that they’ve made it to the Crown of Cuwenn, a field of sharp, protruding rock formations that circle the Isles of Thess. Making it through this hazardous terrain will require all their skill and effort.</p><p>Navigating the Crown of Cuwenn is a skill challenge. Starting in initiative order, each character must choose an action that can be resolved through an ability check (DC 15) to somehow assist the crew of the Fairy Queen. The action must be one that the DM determines to be plausible. If the characters can achieve 6 successes before 3 failures, the ship makes it through the Crown with minimal damage. If they fail to do so, the ship survives the ordeal, but takes damage, and the characters are considered to start with -1 successes when they attempt to land the Fairy Queen in @UUID[.Q8uN6tQkxzdJEjko]{Port of Call} .</p><p></p><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\"><tbody><tr><td><p><span style=\"color:rgb( 231 , 99 , 99 )\">! O Captain! My Captain! The Crown of Cuwenn is an excellent opportunity to endear the characters to Errol. Consider having the captain intermittently provide the help action to needy characters through some daring act of seafaring bravado – or even adding him to the initiative order and letting him contribute directly.</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":400000,"name":"Call of the Deep","type":"text","_id":"IQWMuZje6XvYzSp0","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>On the sixth night of travel, as the first hints of morning begin to peek through the thick grey mist, Lady Sarenya’s minions attack the Fairy Queen, intent on stealing Errol away.</p><blockquote><p>Read out: “The cramped interior of the Fairy Queen sways gently, lit only by thin streaks of pale morning light that cut between small nooks in the hull. Suddenly, the silence is shattered by the sound of something outside striking the water hard, and the ship’s hull begins to shudder ominously…”</p></blockquote><p>The splash the characters hear is that of Errol dropping into the water after having been entranced by three  @UUID[JournalEntry.2f3mNI4pjB1Da331.JournalEntryPage.iH9J4uUznmCJVzby]{Thessidian Vampire}that lurk off the Fairy Queen’s starboard quarter. If the characters rush to the top deck, Errol is 20 ft. beneath the water and is being grappled by one of the vampires when they emerge. If they delay their response, he is already 80 ft. down by the time the characters reach the scene.</p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>Vampires of the Deep</strong></span>. The vampires are there to steal away Errol, and do not concern themselves with other matters. When the characters reach the topdeck, they will use their Haunting Song to draw the characters away from the captain and prevent his rescue. The vampire nearest to Errol will attempt to dive deep under the water with him and use her full movement to take him far from the battle, where the characters cannot follow.</p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>Bringer of Storms</strong></span>. When the characters emerge, the @UUID[JournalEntry.2f3mNI4pjB1Da331.JournalEntryPage.Q9E31wa6akhnrWLP]{Stormbringer Leviathan} – fully under the vampires’ command – rears up from the water and attacks, clambering upon the ship and doing its best to prevent the characters from interfering. The intense storm that the leviathan brings with it ensures that the rest of the crew are occupied with keeping the Fairy Queen from being destroyed.</p><p>As the leviathan emerges, an immense wave rocks the Fairy Queen. Characters must make a DC 16 Dexterity saving throw or be knocked prone and flung to the side of the ship opposite it.</p><p>The leviathan should use its Water Spear ability in its opening round to knock characters prone and cause massive damage to the Fairy Queen. When it has 60 or less hit points, or two rounds after the vampires have taken Errol so deep that retrieving him is unfeasible, the leviathan submerges once again and departs, returning to its post at @UUID[JournalEntry.4oGPNmfFpv6uUHoR.JournalEntryPage.07GxBSG8E1xnBbNO]{The Lighthouse of Thess}.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":500000,"name":"Port of Call","type":"text","_id":"Q8uN6tQkxzdJEjko","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p></p><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\"><tbody><tr><td><h3 style=\"font-family:\"><span style=\"font-family:\">The Athersen Line</span></h3><p>For as long as anyone on the Isles of Thess can remember, the Atherserns have been chosen champions of Thess, serving under the priesthood and each decade using their inherent magical power to banish the Stormbringer Leviathan.</p><p style=\"letter-spacing:normal\"></p><p style=\"letter-spacing:normal\">In truth, however, the Athersens are Thess’ own descendants, and once ruled the isles in her place. When Lady Sarenya took power, she allowed the Athersens to survive, erasing the memory of their previous rank. It was her hope that one day an Athersen descendant would demonstrate enough of Thess’ power to serve as a rejuvenating meal for the Elder One, allowing it to regain its former might. The battle against the leviathan each decade is a sham – a play orchestrated by Sarenya to give the Athersens a false sense of purpose and to mollify the isles’ population.</p><p style=\"letter-spacing:normal\">Errol’s departure from the isles did not trouble Sarenya, as he always seemed less powerful than his brother. The ancient vampire has recently discovered ancient texts suggesting that the twin birth heralds the blossoming of Thess’ power back to fullness, however, each twin playing host to the power of one of Thess’ two aspects. Desperate to fix her mistake in allowing Errol’s escape, Lady Sarenya will stop at nothing to place the errant Athersen back under her power.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Immediately after the vampires escape with Errol and the leviathan vanishes beneath the water, the Fairy Queen is still reeling from the sheer power of the latter monster’s conjured storm. Darceri shouts over the chaos that, no matter what has happened, the priority of everyone aboard should be to get the ship under control and guide it safely to harbour upon the Isles of Thess.</p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>On Deck! (Skill Challenge)</strong></span> Bringing the Fairy Queen under control and guiding it safely to land is a skill challenge. Starting in initiative order, each character must choose an action that can be resolved through an ability check (DC 16) to somehow assist the crew of the Fairy Queen. The action must be one that the DM determines to be plausible. The characters cycle through two rounds of this skill challenge. Once they have completed those two rounds, consult the table below to determine where the Fairy Queen makes port.</p><p></p><table class=\"userscript-table userscript-table-bordered\"><tbody><tr><td><p>Successes</p></td><td><p>Landing Point</p></td><td><p>Ship Damage</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1-2</p></td><td><p>A steep cliff within sight of @UUID[JournalEntry.4oGPNmfFpv6uUHoR.JournalEntryPage.07GxBSG8E1xnBbNO]{The Lighthouse of Thess}</p></td><td><p>Severe damage to the port &amp; starboard bow, flooding below deck, and one of the masts is splintered.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>A rocky beach within sight of @UUID[JournalEntry.4oGPNmfFpv6uUHoR.JournalEntryPage.GzTYxcdIwnMVVDAm]{The Wind's Widow}</p></td><td><p>Severe damage to the port &amp; starboard bow, flooding below deck.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>4+</p></td><td><p>@UUID[JournalEntry.4oGPNmfFpv6uUHoR.JournalEntryPage.1PyBm5XZuTlP0nhm]{Saltvine}</p></td><td><p>Severe damage to the port &amp; starboard bow.<br /></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>Aftermath.</strong></span> In the wake of the leviathan’s attack, the Fairy Queen is heavily damaged and many of its crew have sustained injuries from minor to temporarily debilitating. Darceri quickly assesses the situation and begins issuing orders for crewmen to start preparing the ship as best they can, though she will level with the characters that it could take weeks to get the Fairy Queen seaworthy once more.</p><p><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><strong>Rescue Mission</strong></span>. Whether the ship is repaired or not, the crew are unlikely to leave before making a considerable effort to find their captain – something Darceri will make clear to the characters. She has a solid idea of where they have landed, and can give the characters a rough map of the isles sketched from her memory of Errol’s descriptions over the years. This map does not include @UUID[JournalEntry.4oGPNmfFpv6uUHoR.JournalEntryPage.gYiEhGFJyJPbN8IC]{The Moonstones} or @UUID[JournalEntry.4oGPNmfFpv6uUHoR.JournalEntryPage.GzTYxcdIwnMVVDAm]{The Wind's Widow}</p><p>Darceri will organize a small group of crewmen led by Plo’orgk to search in one direction, and recommends that the characters set out in another. Plo’orgk is confident that he will succeed, and willing to wager 20 gp that his party will find the captain first.<br /></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.288","createdTime":1665945809352,"modifiedTime":1665976468866,"lastModifiedBy":"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L"},"_id":"o0JIfEqVIjHoNzsE","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L":3}}
{"name":"Appendix B - NPC's","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Aoife Athersen","type":"text","_id":"73IrpNq3ul3X3c3b","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><br /><strong>Background.</strong> Daughter to Flynn Athersen, Aoife is next in line to inherit the Athersen legacy – and his portion of Thess’ power – should Sarenya’s plan falter. She is shy, somewhat mousy, and generally humble, but has a surprisingly pragmatic outlook and can think quickly when pressed to do so.</p><p>With Flynn’s disappearance and assumed death, Aoife is being prepared to take on her father’s role, but glimpses of memories repressed by Sarenya’s minions have convinced her that something is amiss. She is uncertain of what to do, but should the characters explain their own situation to her, she will become determined to get to the bottom of the situation, and will do whatever she can to help them.</p><p>Equipment. Lantern, 3 vials of lantern oil, Wardstone, 20 sp. <br /></p><section class=\"secret\" id=\"secret-n9YFc1n7OSrnosak\"><p>GM Notes :</p><blockquote><p>Read out: “The skinny young girl before you seems between sixteen and seventeen, with dark bags under her eyes and darker hair that streaks down her back. She wears a simple, white frock with a dull grey cloak over her shoulders. Her eyes shine a cold, clear blue.”</p></blockquote></section>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Siobhan","type":"text","_id":"aUcTxx4HGIcsM8TI","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Background. </strong>Siobhan is a young priestess of Thess, one of the many lantern girls tasked with maintaining the few remaining safe routes through the mist. She is an orphan, her parents disposed of by Lady Sarenya’s minions, and the Thessidines are her surrogate family. Siobhan is one of the few Thessidines that knows some measure of the truth about Sarenya and the priesthood, having been molded into a loyal servant through extensive memory alteration. She sees Sarenya as the rightful ruler of Thess and has been raised to believe that being granted an eternal unlife as one of her servants is the highest imaginable honour.</p><p>Siobhan is inquisitive, mischievous, and tactically coy. She has a wry sense of humour, and seems highly energetic compared to many of the isles’ citizens, making her popular and endearing.</p><p>She will attempt to latch onto the characters upon sight, hoping that by drawing out as much information from them as possible, she can please Sarenya and earn her favour.</p><p>Equipment. Lantern, 3 vials of lantern oil, Dagger, 12 sp. <br /></p><section class=\"secret\" id=\"secret-brAqpZFqB0DHN3TW\"><p>GM Notes :</p><blockquote><p>Read out: “Reclining against the stone is a slim, pale young girl garbed in a modest dress, her long red hair tumbling across the grey cloak she wears atop her shoulders. A lantern hangs from one of her hands, and her green eyes widen as she notices you.” .</p></blockquote><p></p></section>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Trianna Darceri","type":"text","_id":"zBNi8V2aDllXRiKn","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Background.</strong> First mate to the Fairy Queen, Trianna began her career upon the high seas as an errant ne'er do well, sailing in search of adventure and plunder with a crew of notable corsairs. When her companions ran afoul of the Drakkari Ascendancy’s far-reaching navy, she escaped with her life only by the intervention of Errol Athersen and his crew.</p><p>Trianna has served under the captain since then, and has grown into an experienced, capable, and shrewd seafarer, though she retains her love of adventure. She is a fast talker with quick wits and a penchant for sly commentary, and harbours a persistent weakness for gambling.</p><p>Darceri is Errol’s closest ear and his most trusted confidant, and the two have cultivated a deep loyalty to one another over years.</p><p>Equipment. Rapier, Studded Leather Armour, x3 Daggers, 150 gp. </p><section class=\"secret\" id=\"secret-3fyqagnDA8IKuJjt\"><p>GM Notes :</p><blockquote><p>Read out: “Clad in an odd arrangement of furs, rough leathers, and glittering gold bangles, the woman before you has the lithe build of a trained acrobat. A rapier hangs at her hip, and the many baubles and chimes in her long blonde hair catch the light as she moves.”  </p></blockquote><p></p></section>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":400000,"name":"Eamon","type":"text","_id":"Q9ard55sHTGmOBei","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Statistics. </strong>Commoner, Basic Rules.</p><p><strong>Background.</strong> Once a shepherd by trade, Eamon is one of the elders of Cress. Up until recently, his wisdom and wit was well regarded by his fellow villagers, but then the Waning came for him. As his memory began to degrade and his sight faded, he became prone to unfocused wandering, and is now taken care of by his granddaughter Eire.</p><p>Eamon is lost and confused when the characters find him, having tried to, in a moment of particularly poor lucidity, tried to return to his old home in the long-abandoned village of Saltvine. He doesn’t understand why the village is empty, or exactly where he is or why, and after stumbling in the mist has acquired a bloody head injury.</p><p>If not helped back to Cress, he will likely wander the mists until he bleeds out.</p><section class=\"secret\" id=\"secret-sqrw2LTJ1hndmr5H\"><p>GM Notes :</p><blockquote><p>Read out: “Crouched to one side of the overgrown dirt path that leads out of town, an aging man somewhere in the vicinity of his sixties squints up at you with white, glassy eyes. His clothes are rough, his hair is thin and grey, and he nurses a bloody wound that cuts along one side of his head.”</p></blockquote><p></p></section>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":500000,"name":"Dairine","type":"text","_id":"00GvYiWAEsM7dJkc","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Statistics</strong>. See Thessidian Ancient </p><p><strong>Background.</strong> Dairíne was once a mortal woman, a devotee of Thess’ temple serving under Lady Sarenya. Like many of the most devoted Thessidines, she earned Sarenya’s favour and was transformed into a vampiric mockery of her former self.</p><p>It has been over two centuries since then, and Dairíne has come to hate and fear her mistress in equal measure. She remains loyal not because she remains a believer in Sarenya’s cult, but because the psychic bond between them makes betrayal all but impossible.</p><p>Dairíne is a careful, cunning creature and a practiced liar, very much used to both deceiving Sarenya’s flock and placating her mistress’ whims. She serves as second in command under Sarenya, but if offered some means to escape her influence, Dairíne could be convinced to betray the elder vampire.<br /></p><section class=\"secret\" id=\"secret-vzcVniSMgpdY6uAe\"><p>GM Notes :</p><blockquote><p>Read out: “The woman before you wears loose, flowing vestments that ripple and flow across her slender drame, their hems touched with traces of woven silver. She has shining black hair that she sweeps back into a single long tail, high cheekbones, and dark, inquisitive eyes that roam you up and down.”</p></blockquote><p></p></section>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.288","createdTime":1665949752124,"modifiedTime":1665976468871,"lastModifiedBy":"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L"},"_id":"qJg4GYQDMSUG8Wxt","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"cP1aqbcSMQN2jq1L":3}}
